<subSubSection id="C354656399601101FD77FEB6FC78FE3B" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BF136E899601101FD77FEB6FC78FE3B" blockId="97.[699,1227,193,485]" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">
ETYMOLOGY: The trivial name 
<taxonomicName id="4C4E4D6B99601101FBECFEB7FB2AFE8E" authorityName="OPITZ" authorityYear="2005" box="[1091,1177,313,336]" class="Insecta" family="Cleridae" genus="Aphelocerus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="97" pageNumber="98" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="inbatus">
<emphasis id="B93AEAFA99601101FBECFEB7FB2AFE8E" box="[1091,1177,313,336]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">inbatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a Latin compound adjective that stems from the prefix ­ 
<emphasis id="B93AEAFA99601101FCEAFEFAFCEFFE55" box="[837,860,372,395]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">in</emphasis>
(without) and 
<emphasis id="B93AEAFA99601101FBB7FEFAFBE4FE55" box="[1048,1111,372,395]" italics="true" pageId="97" pageNumber="98">batus</emphasis>
(bush). I refer to the absence of a well­defined setal tuft on the frons present in specimens of closely related species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
